gyptians/women_01.shtml Ancient Egypt and the Role of Women] by Dr Joann Fletcher\n* [http://www.civilization.org.uk/egypt Full-length account of Ancient Egypt as part of history of the world ]\n\n{{Ancient Egypt topics}}\n{{Empires}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Egypt| ]]\n[[Category:Former empires in Africa|Egypt]]\n[[Category:Former empires in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 1 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Egypt"}
{"title_page": "9 (Lil' Kim album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = 9\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Lil' Kim]]\n| cover        = Lil Kim 9 cover.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = October 11, 2019\n| recorded     = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[trap music|trap]]}}\n| length       = 30:59\n| label        = {{hlist|[[Queen Bee Entertainment]]|[[Entertainment One Music|eOne]]}}\n| producer     = {{hlist|Xtassy|Jonny Chash|[[808 Mafia]]}}\n| prev_title   = [[Lil Kim Season]]\n| prev_year    = 2016\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{singles\n| name        = 9\n| type        = studio\n| single1     = Go Awff\n| single1date = February 15, 2019\n| single2     = Found You (feat. [[City Girls]] & [[O.T. Genasis]])\n| single2date = September 27, 2019\n| single3     = Pray For Me (feat. [[Rick Ross]])\n| single3date = October 3, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''9''''' is the fifth [[studio album]] by American rapper [[Lil' Kim]]. It was released on October 11, 2019, through [[Queen Bee Entertainment]] and [[Entertainment One Music|eOne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/03/26/lil-kim-new-album-9-go-awff-the-xx|title=Lil' Kim announces new album 9 out in May|work=[[The Fader]]|date=March 26, 2019|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> The single \"Go Awff\" was released on February 15, 2019. During the taping of [[VH1]]'s ''[[Girls Cruise]]'' reunion episode, Kim confirmed her intention to release the second volume of ''9'' in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-kims-9-is-a-two-part-album-that-will-be-released-really-soon-news.92076.html|title=Lil Kim's \"9\" Has a Sequel Album That Will Be Released \"Really Soon\"|date=October 1, 2019|work=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=October 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn March 23, 2019, Lil' Kim announced that the album would be released on May 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2019/03/24/lil-kim-new-album-nine/|title=Lil' Kim Reveals Release Date for New Album 'Nine'|date=March 24, 2019|work=[[Source (magazine)|Source]]|accessdate=March 26, 2019}}</ref> The rapper described the meaning behind her fifth album in an interview with [[BET]] on the red carpet at the [[BET Awards 2019|2019 BET Awards]]: \"It's a spiritual awakening number for me. Also, when I started out in [[Junior M.A.F.I.A.]] it was 9 members, my daughter was born June 9th, [[The Notorious B.I.G.|Biggie]] died March 9th, it is 2019. It's a powerful number for me. (...) I'm very spiritual and one day God was talking to me and I was like '7 is my favorite number' and He was like 'yes but 9 is your favored number' and I said thank you Jesus, I love you. I'm going with 9.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thegrio.com/2019/07/16/lil-kim-says-new-album-9-is-a-spiritual-awakening-that-number-is-very-powerful-for-me/|title=Lil Kim says new album \u20189\u2019 is a spiritual awakening: \u2018That number is very powerful for me\u2019|date=July 16, 2019|website=[[The Grio]]|accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> In April, she announced that the label [[Entertainment One Music|eOne]] had decided to push back the release of the album<ref>{{cite web |url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2019/04/23/lil-kim-blasts-label-for-holding-back-album-also-has-words-for-spotify-i-am-beyond-upset/ |title=Lil' Kim Blasts Label For Holding Back Album, Also Has Words For Spotify: 'I Am Beyond Upset' |author=Daryl Nelson |date=April 23, 2019 |publisher=atlantablackstar.com |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> which was then expected to premier in July 2019 to coincide with Kim's reality show ''[[Girls Cruise]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/lil-kims-new-album-9-will-be-released-in-july-alongside-her-new-reality-tv-show-18184583 |title=Lil Kim's New Album '9' Will Be Released In July Alongside Her New Reality TV Show |author=Tai Gooden |date=July 15, 2019 |publisher=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Promotion ==\nThe 2018 song \"[[Nasty One]]\", previously slated as the album's first single, eventually was not included in the track list. \"Go Awff\", released in February 2019,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/go-awff-single/1452913544?app=itunes |title=Go Awff - Single by Lil' Kim on iTunes |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> instead became the lead single, with a music video released in March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ebBPZ_J2cHs |title=Lil' Kim - Go Awff (Official Video) - YouTube |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref> In April, the rapper released a promotional single \"No Auto Blanco\" exclusively for streaming on [[SoundCloud]].<ref name=\"rap-up\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rap-up.com/2019/04/23/lil-kim-delays-9-album-release/ |title=Lil' Kim Delays '9' Album Release |date=April 23, 2019 |publisher=[[Rap-Up]] |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> It was followed by the second official single \"Found You\" featuring [[O.T. Genasis]] and [[City Girls]] in September 2019. On October 3, Lil' Kim released the third single, \"Pray for Me\", featuring [[Rick Ross]] and [[Musiq Soulchild]], and confirmed October 11 as the final release date of the album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-kim-links-with-rick-ross-on-pray-for-me-new-song.1984726.html |title=Lil Kim Links With Rick Ross On \"Pray For Me\" |author=Mitch Findlay |date=October 3, 2019 |publisher=www.hotnewhiphop.com |accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref> Although originally reported as consisting of 13 tracks,<ref name=\"rap-up\"/> the album eventually featured only nine songs. The previously confirmed song \"Missing\" was left off the album.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8464926/lil-kim-debuts-new-track-nasty-one-talks-early-censorship |title=Lil' Kim Debuts New Track, 'Nasty One,' Talks Early Censorship & Everlasting Legacy |author=Kathy Iandoli |date=July 11, 2018 |publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLil' Kim has confirmed that the second part of ''9'' will be released at a later date and that it will feature a song with [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Paris Hilton]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nCdHQs0IQEI |title=Lil' Kim Talks Her New, Highly-Anticipated Album, \"9\" |date=October 8, 2019 |publisher=www.youtube.com |accessdate=October 14, 2019}}</ref> as well as collaborations with [[Remy Ma]], [[Fabolous]], both of whom she has collaborated with in the past, on \"[[Wake Me Up (Remy Ma song)|Wake Me Up]]\" and \"Spicy\", respectively and comedian Pretty Vee who featured on ''Girls Cruise''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xbak40TlY6c |title=Lil' Kim - talks Beyonc\u00e9, Drake, New Album, City Girls and more |publisher=www.youtube.com |accessdate=October 20, 2019}}</ref> The first part of ''9'' was released as a deluxe edition to CD which featured \u201cNasty One (Remix)\u201d as a bonus track. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07ZLJ6KQZ/ |title=Lil' Kim - 9 (Deluxe Edition) |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album was on [[NPR]]'s \"best new albums of the week\" at the time of its release,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/10/769095091/new-music-friday-our-top-6-albums-out-oct-11|title=New Music Friday: Our Top 6 Albums Out Oct. 11|website=NPR.org|accessdate=October 12, 2019}}</ref> and was met with mixed to positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soulinstereo.com/2019/10/album-review-lil-kim-9.html |title=Album Review: Lil Kim, 9 |author=Edward Bowser |date=October 11, 2019 |publisher=www.soulinstereo.com |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blackboybulletin.com/2019/10/11/album-review-lil-kim-9/ |title=Album Review: Lil\u2019 Kim, \u20189\u2019 |author=Kyle Denis |date=October 11, 2019 |publisher=blackboybulletin.com |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bcheights.com/2019/10/21/lil-kim-explores-new-sound-on-long-awaited-9/ |title=Lil\u2019 Kim Explores New Sound on Long-Awaited \u20189\u2019 |author=Tonie Chase |date=October 21, 2019 |publisher=bcheights.com |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Jordan Bassett of ''[[NME]]'' rated the album 3 out of 5 stars and described it as \"lewd, contrarian and confrontational \u2013 all the qualities that make Kim an icon\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/lil-kim-9-review |title=Lil Kim \u2013 '9' review |author=Jordan Bassett |date=October 16, 2019 |publisher=www.nme.com |accessdate=October 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''9'' did not make an impact on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] or any other national chart which incorporates [[Streaming media|streaming]] figures, but it reached number 7 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s hip-hop album sales chart and number 47 on ''Billboard''{{'}}s overall album sales chart, and entered sales-only charts in the UK and France.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length    = 30:59\n| title1          = Pray for Me\n| note1           = featuring [[Rick Ross]] and [[Musiq Soulchild]]\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Lil' Kim|Kimberly Jones]]|Taalib Johnson|William Roberts}}\n| extra1          = Xtassy\n| length1         = 4:51\n| title2          = Bag\n| writer2         = Jones\n| extra2          =\n| length2         = 3:47\n| title3          = Catch My Wave \n| note3           = featuring [[Rich the Kid]]\n| writer3         = Jones\n| extra3          =\n| length3         = 3:49\n| title4          = Go Awff\n| writer4         = Jones\n| extra4          = Soundwave\n| length4         = 3:12\n| title5          = Too Bad\n| writer5         = Jones\n| extra5          =\n| length5         = 3:39\n| title6          = You Are Not 