59-6}}\n* {{cite book |author=Tite, Colin G. C. |title=The Early Records of Sir Robert Cotton's Library: Formation, Cataloguing, Use |publisher=British Library |year=2003 |location=London|isbn=0-7123-4824-7}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |author=van Houts, Elizabeth |title=Historical Writing |encyclopedia =A Companion to the Anglo-Norman World |editor1=Harper-Bill, Christopher |editor2=van Houts, Elizabeth |publisher=Boydell |location=Woodbridge, UK |year=2002 |isbn=978-1-84383-341-3 |pages=103\u2013121 }}\n* {{cite book |author=Williams, Ann |authorlink= Ann Williams (historian) |title=Aethelred the Unready: The Ill-Counselled King |publisher=Hambledon & London |location=London |year= 2003  |isbn=1-85285-382-4 }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |author=Williams, Ann |authorlink=Ann Williams (historian) |title=The Cunning of the Dove: Wulfstan and the Politics of Accommodation |editor=Brooks, Nicholas |editor2=Barrow, Julia |encyclopedia=St. Wulfstan and His World |publisher=Ashgate |location=Aldershot, UK |year=2005 |pages=23\u201338 |isbn=0-7546-0802-6 }}\n* {{cite book |author=Williams, Ann |authorlink= Ann Williams (historian) |title=The English and the Norman Conquest |publisher=Boydell Press |location=Woodbridge, UK |year=2000 |isbn=0-85115-708-4 }}\n* {{cite journal |author=Williams, Ann |authorlink= Ann Williams (historian)  |title=The Spoliation of Worcester |journal=Anglo-Norman Studies |year=1997 |volume=19 |pages=383\u2013408 |isbn= 0851157076}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia |author=Barrow, J. |title=How the Twelfth-Century Monks of Worcester Preserved Their Past |encyclopedia=The Perception of the Past in Twelfth-Century Europe |editor=Magdalino, P.  |year=1992 |location=London |pages=53\u201374}}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia |author=Tinti, Francesca. |title=''Si litterali memorie commendaretur'': Memory and Cartularies in Eleventh-century Worcester |encyclopedia=Early Medieval Studies in Memory of Patrick Wormald |editor=Baxter, Stephen| series=Studies in Early Medieval Britain |year=2009 |location=Farnham, UK |publisher=Ashgate |pages=475\u2013497|display-editors=etal}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [[Thomas Hearne (antiquarian)|Hearne, Thomas]]. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=wVAVAAAAQAAJ Hemingi chartularium ecclesi\u00e6 Wigorniensis]''. 2 vols. Oxford, 1723.\n* [https://www.le.ac.uk/english/em1060to1220/mss/EM.BL.Tibe.A.xiii.htm ''Liber Wigorniensis'' and Hemming's Cartulary], London, [[British Library|BL]], Cotton Tiberius A XIII, fos. 1\u2013118, 119\u2013200.\n* [http://individual.utoronto.ca/emrecordkeeping/Pages/WorcesterCartulariesHome.html Early Worcester Records], University of Toronto.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121016155721/http://www.bl.uk/catalogues/manuscripts/HITS0001.ASP?VPath=html%2F73750.htm&Search=Cott.+Nero+E.i.&Highlight=F Cotton Nero E i] British Library description page for MS Cotton Nero E i\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121016155800/http://www.bl.uk/catalogues/manuscripts/HITS0001.ASP?VPath=html%2F1251.htm&Search=Add.+46204&Highlight=F Add. MS 46204] British Library description page for Add. MS 46204\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hemming's Cartulary}}\n[[Category:11th-century manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Texts of Anglo-Saxon England]]\n[[Category:Cotton Library]]\n[[Category:English chronicles]]\n[[Category:English manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Historical writing from Norman and Angevin England]]\n[[Category:Medieval charters and cartularies of England]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eContents:Typo fixing, replaced: Spoilation \u2192 Spoliation, as shown in the References section", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hemming%27s_Cartulary"}
{"title_page": "Mavji Maheshwari", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n'''Mavji Maheshwari''' ({{lang-gu|\u0aae\u0abe\u0ab5\u0a9c\u0ac0 \u0aae\u0ab9\u0ac7\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab0\u0ac0}}) is a Gujarati short story writer and novelist, chiefly known for his fiction based on the life in [[Kutch district|Kutch region]]. He was born on 30 December 1964 in Bhojay, a village in [[Mandvi]] of [[Kutch district]], [[Gujarat]], India.<ref name=\"GujLit\">{{cite web | last=GujLit | first=\u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0ab2\u0abf\u0a9f\u0ab0\u0ac7\u0a9a\u0ab0 ! | title=\u0aae\u0abe\u0ab5\u0a9c\u0ac0 \u0aae\u0ab9\u0ac7\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab0\u0ac0 | website=GujLit | url=http://gujlit.com/profile.php?pId=54 | language=gu | access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref><ref name=\"PrasadGaijan2007\">{{cite book|author1=Amar Nath Prasad|author2=M. B. Gaijan|title=Dalit Literature: A Critical Exploration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bg0rOOqvBMkC&pg=PA221|year=2007|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-817-3|page=221}}</ref><ref name=KantiMalatsar>{{cite book |last=Malatsar |first=Kanti |title=Gujarati Sahityama Kutch Pradeshni Chhabi |year=2018 |publisher=Parshva Publication |location=Ahmedabad |page=141 |isbn=978-93-5108-883-7}}</ref>\n\nHe published his first short story collection ''Adrashya Diwalo'' in 2000, which is followed by ''Ratt-Kachchhi Vartao'' (2008), ''Vijog'' (2009), ''Pavan'' (2009), ''Hastrekha'' (2012), ''Surprise'' (2016) and ''Khovai Gayeli Gaam'' (2016). ''Melo'', is first novel, was published in 2007, followed by ''Meghadambar'' (2008), ''Kaandhno Hak'' (2009), ''Aganbaan'' (2013) and ''Ajani Disha'' (2015). ''Ranbheri'' (2008) and ''Bor'' (2009) are two of his collections of plays.<ref name=\"GujLit\"/><ref name=KantiMalatsar/>\n\nHe received several prizes from [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] and [[Gujarat Sahitya Academy]] for his books. He is also a recipient of Kabir Award, Kakasaheb Kalelkar Prize, Jayant Khatri Award and Kala Gurjari Prize.<ref name=\"GujLit\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Gujarati-language writers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{GujLit author}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maheshwari, Mavji}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Mandvi]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Indian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male writers]]\n\n\n{{India-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n'''Mavji Maheshwari''' ({{lang-gu|\u0aae\u0abe\u0ab5\u0a9c\u0ac0 \u0aae\u0ab9\u0ac7\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab0\u0ac0}}) is a Gujarati short story writer and novelist, chiefly known for his fiction based on the life in [[Kutch district|Kutch region]]. He was born on 30 December 1964 in Bhojay, a village in [[Mandvi]] of [[Kutch district]], [[Gujarat]], India.<ref name=\"GujLit\">{{cite web | last=GujLit | first=\u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0ab2\u0abf\u0a9f\u0ab0\u0ac7\u0a9a\u0ab0 ! | title=\u0aae\u0abe\u0ab5\u0a9c\u0ac0 \u0aae\u0ab9\u0ac7\u0ab6\u0acd\u0ab5\u0ab0\u0ac0 | website=GujLit | url=http://gujlit.com/profile.php?pId=54 | language=gu | access-date=2017-11-18}}</ref><ref name=\"PrasadGaijan2007\">{{cite book|author1=Amar Nath Prasad|author2=M. B. Gaijan|title=Dalit Literature: A Critical Exploration|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bg0rOOqvBMkC&pg=PA221|year=2007|publisher=Sarup & Sons|isbn=978-81-7625-817-3|page=221}}</ref><ref name=KantiMalatsar>{{cite book |last=Malatsar |first=Kanti |title=Gujarati Sahityama Kutch Pradeshni Chhabi |year=2018 |publisher=Parshva Publication |location=Ahmedabad |page=141 |isbn=978-93-5108-883-7}}</ref>\n\nHe published his first short story collection ''Adrashya Diwalo'' in 2000, which is followed by ''Ratt-Kachchhi Vartao'' (2008), ''Vijog'' (2009), ''Pavan'' (2009), ''Hastrekha'' (2012), ''Surprise'' (2016) and ''Khovai Gayeli Gaam'' (2016). ''Melo'', is first novel, was published in 2007, followed by ''Meghadambar'' (2008), ''Kaandhno Hak'' (2009), ''Aganbaan'' (2013) and ''Ajani Disha'' (2015). ''Ranbheri'' (2008) and ''Bor'' (2009) are two of his collections of plays.<ref name=\"GujLit\"/><ref name=KantiMalatsar/>\n\nHe received several prizes from [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] and [[Gujarat Sahitya Academy]] for his books. He is also a recipient of Kabir Award, Kakasaheb Kalelkar Prize, Jayant Khatri Award and Kala Gurjari Prize.<ref name=\"GujLit\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Gujarati-language writers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{GujLit author}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maheshwari, Mavji}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kutch district]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Indian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male writers]]\n\n\n{{India-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mavji_Maheshwari"}
